			"seed": 834805669,
			"version": 533,
			"versionNonce": 196307336,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1777284410052,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "BACKLOG:\n\nthink about the ImageBuild deleting logic.\n\nIf used by container, prohibit removal.\nIf used only by image, prohibit removal.\n\nIf we want to change the build for\nMachineImage, we just assign a different\nbuild.\n\nProblem: should assigning result in removing\nold build or leave it as is?\n\nProblem: how do we clean up build when all\nusing containers are deleted?",
			"rawText": "BACKLOG:\n\nthink about the ImageBuild deleting logic.\n\nIf used by container, prohibit removal.\nIf used only by image, prohibit removal.\n\nIf we want to change the build for MachineImage, we just assign a different build.\n\nProblem: should assigning result in removing old build or leave it as is?\n\nProblem: how do we clean up build when all using containers are deleted?",
			"fontSize": 36,
			"fontFamily": 5,
			"textAlign": "center",
			"verticalAlign": "middle",
			"containerId": "3CHK6t7u",
			"originalText": "BACKLOG:\n\nthink about the ImageBuild deleting logic.\n\nIf used by container, prohibit removal.\nIf used only by image, prohibit removal.\n\nIf we want to change the build for MachineImage, we just assign a different build.\n\nProblem: should assigning result in removing old build or leave it as is?\n\nProblem: how do we clean up build when all using containers are deleted?",
			"autoResize": true,
			"lineHeight": 1.25,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"link": null
		},
		{
			"id": "thtSWFAt",
			"type": "rectangle",
			"x": 10238.110443027394,
			"y": -1249.1697094665178,
			"width": 1884.6821584923507,
			"height": 2499.774616017742,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
			"backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 2,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 0,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"frameId": null,
			"index": "b1F",
			"roundness": {
				"type": 3
			},
			"seed": 197770825,
			"version": 554,
			"versionNonce": 1385229256,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1777279878748,
			"link": null,
			"locked": false,
			"hasTextLink": false
		},
		{
			"id": "FcqAxBmG",
			"type": "text",
			"x": 10395.260699521692,
			"y": -1137.7322454610553,
			"width": 1394.49658203125,
			"height": 2475,
			"angle": 0,
			"strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
			"backgroundColor": "#b2f2bb",
			"fillStyle": "solid",
			"strokeWidth": 2,
			"strokeStyle": "solid",
			"roughness": 0,
			"opacity": 100,
			"groupIds": [],
			"frameId": null,
			"index": "b1H",
			"roundness": null,
			"seed": 1155253385,
			"version": 2157,
			"versionNonce": 1209021128,
			"isDeleted": false,
			"boundElements": [],
			"updated": 1777279878748,
			"locked": false,
			"text": "Design: On ImageBuild lifecycle\n\nVersion: 1.0\n\nContainer\n    docker_container_id\n    build_in_use: ref->MachineImageBuild\n\nMachineImage\n    name\n    active_build\n\nMachineImageBuild\n    tag\n    docker_file_code\n    docker_image_id\n    deprecated -- bool, default=False\n\nMachineImage specifies generic VM ware (ex.: ubuntu 24.04).\nMachineImageBuild -- read-only builds. Every rebuild\nresults in creating a new replica record and setting\nthe original record as deprecated. \n\n\nThis allows\nthe containers using the original build to finish their lifetime.\n\nIn replication, if the original build is not being used by\nany container and MachineImage, we can safely delete it.\nOtherwise, we add to the job that runs clean up\non deprecated builds.\n\nTwo solutions to make the MachineImage using the\noriginal build to use rebuilt one:\n    - schedule job to update active_build of all\n    MachineImage instanes to use the new build.\n    - let the admin do it manually.\n\nBoth options seem feasible due to the system being\nnaturally small in this usecase.\n\nOne bad side of replicating is that Dockerfile is replicated\nevery time. Two approaches:\n    - Set the deprecated build's Dockerfile to empty when Dockerfile\n        hasn't been changed in rebuild..\n    - Keep it.\n\n\nWHAT IF: we stored docker image directly on container, not build?\n                Seems quite efficient. Needs analysis.\n\nTHIS SOLUTION CAME BECAUSE OF: what happens when we do rebuild\nin the previous design? The container would reference the same build. But that\nbuild would container rebuild's docker image id when we want the container\nto be linked with older build! This naturally forces replication.",
			"rawText": "Design: On ImageBuild lifecycle\n\nVersion: 1.0\n\nContainer\n    docker_container_id\n    build_in_use: ref->MachineImageBuild\n\nMachineImage\n    name\n    active_build\n\nMachineImageBuild\n    tag\n    docker_file_code\n    docker_image_id\n    deprecated -- bool, default=False\n\nMachineImage specifies generic VM ware (ex.: ubuntu 24.04).\nMachineImageBuild -- read-only builds. Every rebuild\nresults in creating a new replica record and setting\nthe original record as deprecated. \n\n\nThis allows\nthe containers using the original build to finish their lifetime.\n\nIn replication, if the original build is not being used by\nany container and MachineImage, we can safely delete it.\nOtherwise, we add to the job that runs clean up\non deprecated builds.\n\nTwo solutions to make the MachineImage using the\noriginal build to use rebuilt one:\n    - schedule job to update active_build of all\n    MachineImage instanes to use the new build.\n    - let the admin do it manually.\n\nBoth options seem feasible due to the system being\nnaturally small in this usecase.\n\nOne bad side of replicating is that Dockerfile is replicated\nevery time. Two approaches:\n    - Set the deprecated build's Dockerfile to empty when Dockerfile\n        hasn't been changed in rebuild..\n    - Keep it.\n\n\nWHAT IF: we stored docker image directly on container, not build?\n                Seems quite efficient. Needs analysis.\n\nTHIS SOLUTION CAME BECAUSE OF: what happens when we do rebuild\nin the previous design? The container would reference the same build. But that\nbuild would container rebuild's docker image id when we want the container\nto be linked with older build! This naturally forces replication.",
			"fontSize": 36,
			"fontFamily": 5,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "Design: On ImageBuild lifecycle\n\nVersion: 1.0\n\nContainer\n    docker_container_id\n    build_in_use: ref->MachineImageBuild\n\nMachineImage\n    name\n    active_build\n\nMachineImageBuild\n    tag\n    docker_file_code\n    docker_image_id\n    deprecated -- bool, default=False\n\nMachineImage specifies generic VM ware (ex.: ubuntu 24.04).\nMachineImageBuild -- read-only builds. Every rebuild\nresults in creating a new replica record and setting\nthe original record as deprecated. \n\n\nThis allows\nthe containers using the original build to finish their lifetime.\n\nIn replication, if the original build is not being used by\nany container and MachineImage, we can safely delete it.\nOtherwise, we add to the job that runs clean up\non deprecated builds.\n\nTwo solutions to make the MachineImage using the\noriginal build to use rebuilt one:\n    - schedule job to update active_build of all\n    MachineImage instanes to use the new build.\n    - let the admin do it manually.\n\nBoth options seem feasible due to the system being\nnaturally small in this usecase.\n\nOne bad side of replicating is that Dockerfile is replicated\nevery time. Two approaches:\n    - Set the deprecated build's Dockerfile to empty when Dockerfile\n        hasn't been changed in rebuild..\n    - Keep it.\n\n\nWHAT IF: we stored docker image directly on container, not build?\n                Seems quite efficient. Needs analysis.\n\nTHIS SOLUTION CAME BECAUSE OF: what happens when we do rebuild\nin the previous design? The container would reference the same build. But that\nbuild would container rebuild's docker image id when we want the container\nto be linked with older build! This naturally forces replication.",
			"autoResize": true,
			"lineHeight": 1.25,
			"hasTextLink": false,
			"link": null
		},
		{
			"id": "EIRd5bqx",
